<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n13080m"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n13" href="#n13080m">N13 (VI.D.3)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n13all.htm#n13080m"> 80(m)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> saliva scripturae meae</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The term used by Giraldus, however, <i>Hibernic&eacute; scripti</i>, may perhaps mean written in Irish characters. Yet Patrick himself appears to say that he originally wrote in Irish, &ldquo;<i>sermo et loquela mea translata est in linquam alienam sicut facile potest probari ex <mark>saliva scriptur&aelig; me&aelig;</mark></i>,&rdquo; <i>i.e.</i>, &ldquo;My words and language have been translated into another tongue, as may easily be judged from my beslavered writing.&rdquo; <small> Douglas Hyde, <a name="SEGL" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SEGL"><cite title="source">The Story of Early Gaelic Literature</cite></a> (1920) 4 [on Saint Patrick writing in Irish]</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c05019m" href="c5all.htm#c05019m">VI.C.05:019(m)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
